[1] Apple scab, undiagnosed fungi - Czech Republic
Date: Mon 28 Jun 2010
Source: FreshPlaza, Czech Fruit Growers Association report [edited]
<http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=65443>


Fruit volumes down in Czech Republic
------------------------------------
Due to the recent adverse weather conditions earlier in 2010 the fruit
harvest will most likely be below the average of the last few years.
The cold, wet weather just as the fruit trees were blossoming caused
the problems and also led to wide spread fungus diseases. The [yield]
estimate for 2010 is 10 percent lower than in 2009 according to the
Czech Fruit Growers Association.

There is expected to be 60 percent less apricots. The apple harvest is
expected to show a 6 percent drop and there will be less quality fruit
due to widespread scab diseases. Peach volumes will be down around 30
percent and Czech peach orchards are not being renewed because they
cannot [compete with] the Italian and Greek ones. The harvests of
cherries, plums, and pears will be down 6-37 percent on 2009 but the
areas of these crops are increasing.

Orchards cover 17 713 hectares [approx. 43 800 acres] in the Czech
Republic and fruit harvested is worth more than Kc 1 billion [approx.
USD 48.8 million] annually.

[Byline: Nichola Watson]

