[2] Multiple diseases - USA: (Oregon)
Date: Thu 24 Jun 2010
Source: Capital Press [edited]
<http://www.capitalpress.com/content/ml-plant-disease-utopia-062510-art>


Wet weather fuels disease pressure
----------------------------------
Explosion of rare diseases is causing damage across the state's
orchards. Oregon State University's Jay Pscheidt is seeing plant
diseases this spring [2010] that he's never seen in 22 years. In most
cases growers are intensifying treatment programs, but because of
difficulty getting into fields or because of resistance, they are
suffering losses.

In a spring that broke rainfall records, common diseases such as brown
rots, scabs, anthracnose, blossom blights and leaf spots are
flourishing on a variety of fruit crops. Rare diseases also are
showing up. "It's not necessarily the volume of rain as the length of
the wet period (causing the eruptions)," Pscheidt said. "Rusts are
going crazy. The Pacific Coast pear rust has been particularly nasty."

Blueberries are seeing a lot of problem with botrytis. In cherries,
brown rot blossom blight has erupted. Where he didn't spray, Pscheidt
said the blight is causing 50 to 80 percent losses in his cherry
plots. "I have not seen it this bad in the 22 years I've been here,"
he said. Leaf curls and other foliar diseases that can affect next
year's [2011] crops also have erupted. "The foliar diseases, because
of the wet weather, have gone bonkers," Pscheidt said.

And then there are the rare diseases, such as apple rusts. "It's the
1st time I've seen those rustations on apples," Pscheidt said. The
Pacific Coast pear rust, which causes malformation in pears, is common
in the Willamette Valley, but typically isn't economically
significant. This year [2010] it is, Pscheidt said.

[Byline: Mitch Lies]

